[1] USA: preventable deaths
Date: Fri 25 Jun 2021
Source: CIDRAP (Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy) [edited]
https://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2021/06/nearly-all-us-covid-19-deaths-now-preventable


For the 1st time since the COVID-19 pandemic began in earnest in March 2020 in the United States, nearly all of the deaths recorded in recent weeks were preventable, occurring in unvaccinated Americans.

According to an Associated Press analysis of Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) data from May [2021], only about 150 of the more than 18 000 COVID-19 deaths in May were in fully vaccinated people, or less than 1%. This translates to 5 deaths per day attributed to fully vaccinated Americans experiencing breakthrough infections, and roughly 300 deaths per day in the unvaccinated (https://apnews.com/article/coronavirus-pandemic-health-941fcf43d9731c76c16e7354f5d5e187).

Vaccination has also reduced US hospitalizations significantly: Fully vaccinated people made up less than 1200 of more than 853 000 COVID-19 hospitalizations in May [2021].

The United States reported 12 830 new COVID-19 cases yesterday [24 Jun 2021], and 341 deaths, according to the Johns Hopkins COVID-19 tracker (https://coronavirus.jhu.edu/data/cumulative-cases). In total, the nation has confirmed 33 593 763 cases, including 603 238 deaths.

The CDC COVID Data Tracker shows 379 248 700 COVID-19 vaccine doses have been delivered in the United States, and 320 687 205 have been administered, with 151 252 034 Americans fully vaccinated (65.7% of adults have at least one dose; https://covid.cdc.gov/covid-data-tracker/#vaccinations).

About 95% of vaccinated Americans have used a 2-dose mRNA vaccine, either one from Pfizer or Moderna. The vaccination is considered complete 2 weeks after the 2nd dose of vaccine is administered, but more than 1 in 10 people who have received one dose of the Pfizer or Moderna vaccine have missed their 2nd dose, according to CDC data shared with CNN (https://www.cnn.com/2021/06/25/health/us-coronavirus-friday/index.html).

Experts have warned that only one dose of mRNA vaccine offers limited protection against new variants, including the Delta variant (B1617.2).

Southern states [continue] to lag behind Northern and Midwestern states in terms of vaccination rates. Six of the bottom 8 states with the lowest vaccination rates in the country are in the South, including Louisiana, Mississippi, Alabama, Arkansas, Georgia and Tennessee.

Louisiana, which has vaccinated just 34% of its population, has become the latest state to use a lottery prize to entice people to get a COVID-19 vaccine, the New York Times reports (https://www.nytimes.com/2021/06/25/us/louisiana-covid-vaccination-lottery.html). The state will offer a total of USD 2.3 million in cash prizes and scholarships over a month.

The COVID-19 pandemic has impaired the mental health of public health workers, according to a study today in the CDC's Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report (Bryant-Genevier et al. http://dx.doi.org/10.15585/mmwr.mm7026e1).

A total of 26 174 state, tribal, local, and territorial public health workers were surveyed on mental health in the past 2 weeks, and 53% reported symptoms of at least one mental health condition. Of the 53%, 32% reported symptoms of depression, 30.3% anxiety (30.3%), 36.8% post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD), and 8.4% suicidal ideation. Public health workers younger than 30 were most likely to report mental health symptoms.

"Most (92.6%) respondents reported working directly on COVID-19 response activities; the majority (59.2%) worked 41 or more hours in a typical week since March 2020," the authors wrote.

"The prevalences of all 4 mental health outcomes and the severity of symptoms of depression or PTSD increased as the percentage of work time spent directly on COVID-19 response activities and number of work hours in a typical week increased."

[Byline: Stephanie Soucheray]

